# ============================================================================
# BLACKTHORN MANOR — SESSION 1: "THE SÉANCE"
# ============================================================================
#
# DREAM SCENARIO: Blackthorn Manor — Gothic England, October 1873
# GENRE: Gothic Romance (Sincere + Comedy). Jane Austen meets Crimson Peak
#   meets "I'm just trying to do my job."
#
# UNLOCK CONDITIONS:
# - reader.sessions_completed >= 15
# - reader.mystical_affinity >= 6
# - reader.dreams_started == True
#
# CATALYST: Deep dream. Sharper and more vivid than the other dreams.
#   You wake in a carriage you've never been in, wearing clothes
#   you've never owned, clutching a carpetbag that's yours even
#   though you've never seen it. The dream has opinions about who
#   you are: Miss [Name], of Bath. Card reader. Sensible woman.
#   Hired for a weekend party. Five pounds in your purse.
#
# CORE TENSION: You're the only mundane person in a house full of
#   Gothic tropes that turn out to be REAL. Everyone thinks YOU'RE
#   the mystical one. You learned tarot from a BOOK.
#
# TONE: Comedy of manners + genuine supernatural. Sincere Gothic beats
#   played for both laughs AND feeling. The comedy IS the horror:
#   you're stuck here with these people and the bridge is out.
#
# SESSION 1 STRUCTURE:
#   Act 1: Arrival + Rose Room (subtle supernatural — deniable)
#   Act 2: Midnight Dinner (meet everyone, escalating unease)
#   Act 3: The Séance (the reading — ghost appears — UNDENIABLE)
#   Act 4: Hallway Encounter (Ravencroft + Mrs. Winters rescue)
#   Act 5: Bed (alone with questions)
#
# SPREAD: "Through the Veil" (5-card séance spread)
#   Position 1: The Departed (Who was Lord Blackthorn?)
#   Position 2: Their Message (What do they want to say?)
#   Position 3: What They Left Behind
#   Position 4: What's Hidden
#   Position 5: The Truth
#
# CARD POOLS:
#   Position 1: King of Swords / Emperor / Knight of Pentacles
#   Position 2: Seven of Swords / Five of Pentacles / Page of Cups
#   Position 3: Ten of Pentacles / Four of Pentacles / Six of Swords
#   Position 4: The Moon / High Priestess / Eight of Swords
#   Position 5: Three of Swords / Justice / Judgement
#
# REVERSAL CHANCE: 25% (slightly higher than Kind Of — more
#   volatility matches the Gothic atmosphere)
#
# INTERPRETATION AXES:
#   Grounded (best) — reads the cards honestly, stays herself
#   Diplomatic (good) — softens truth for the room, still accurate
#   Gothic (risky) — plays into the drama, fun but loses integrity
#   Panicked (poor) — too rattled to give a proper reading
#
# PATH TRACKING:
#   groundedness — how well she stays "Miss [Name] from Bath"
#     High = best outcomes, earns servant trust, resists house
#     Low = house gains influence, Gothic persona takes over
#   servant_trust — relationship with Mrs. Winters, Thomas, Miss Chen
#   house_influence — how much the house is "noticing" you
#   composure — how rattled she is (depletes, must be managed)
#
# CHARACTERS:
#   Lady Blackthorn — hostess, dramatic, in denial about house's nature
#   Lord Ashford — cursed (real), brooding (default), decent man under it
#   Miss Arabella Grey — actually sees ghosts, fragile, brave
#   Dr. Mordecai Blackwood — "scientist," insufferable, takes notes
#   Lord Ravencroft — the Byronic menace, all performance, no substance
#   Heathsniff — borzoi, dramatic, actually a very good dog
#   Mrs. Winters — housekeeper, protector, been here 40 years
#   Thomas — footman, cheerful, sane, your ally
#   Miss Chen — lady's maid, sardonic, from Guangzhou, eye-rolling partner
#   Mr. Graves — butler, skeletal, thematically consistent
#   Lord Blackthorn's Ghost — appears at séance, angry, dead
#
# THE HOUSE:
#   Blackthorn Manor is not a setting. It's a character.
#   It consumes. Slowly. The servants who "left" didn't leave.
#   Lady Blackthorn genuinely doesn't know — or has convinced
#   herself she doesn't know. "I thought Avery went to the circus."
#   The house sustains itself on the people who serve it.
#   Session 1 plants seeds. Session 3 reveals.
#
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Start ^DREAM:GOTHIC
@py:
# Initialize dream session and persistent client state
session = create_session(blackthorn)
blackthorn.reset_session_tracking()
blackthorn.start_session()

# The dream assigns an identity: Miss [Name], of Bath
# The dream has opinions about who you are
session.player_title = "Miss " + blackthorn.player_name
@endpy

# ============================================================================
# ACT 1: THE ARRIVAL
# ============================================================================

You're at your reading table. Your real one. Your apartment.

The deck is warm in your hands. You've been shuffling without thinking — the way you do when a dream is coming but hasn't arrived yet.

You blink.

The table is gone.

+ [Continue] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Carriage

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Carriage

You are in a carriage.

This is not a gentle transition. There was no dissolve, no mist, no slow fade from your apartment into somewhere else. You were *there* and now you're *here* and the carriage is rattling over gravel and rain is hammering the roof and your hands are gripping a carpetbag you've never seen but recognize completely.

It's yours. Worn leather, brass clasps, one corner slightly scuffed. Inside — you know without looking — your tarot deck (the same one, the real one, warm against your hip through the leather), a spare dress in sensible gray wool, *The Complete Guide to Cartomancy* by Professor Thaddeus Crane (1873 Edition, Hatchards, three shillings), and a very practical umbrella.

Also inside: five pounds in coin. Payment in advance. For the weekend.

You are Miss Amelia Brown, of Bath. You are in your mid-twenties. You are respectable, middle-class, and you read tarot cards for parties and private functions because it pays better than governess work and involves fewer children. You learned this skill from a book. You have never claimed to be mystical, exotic, or "gifted." You placed an advertisement in the *Times*: "Tarot Readings for Parties and Private Functions. Reasonable Rates. References Available."

Lady Blackthorn responded by telegram. The telegram said: *THE CARDS HAVE CALLED YOU TO ME.*

You responded: *My rates are five pounds per weekend engagement. Travel expenses additional.*

She sent twelve pounds. You did not ask questions.

The carriage jolts. Through the rain-streaked window, something looms.

+ [Look] -> Blackthorn.Session1.FirstSight

:: Blackthorn.Session1.FirstSight
Blackthorn Manor.

Turrets. Gargoyles. A quantity of windows that seems unreasonable for a building that isn't a cathedral. The kind of architecture that makes you think "someone was *showing off*" and then "someone was *compensating*" and then "someone was frankly a bit *unwell.*"

The gravel drive is long enough that you have time to count the gargoyles. You stop at fourteen. There are more. Some of them look like they were added later, by someone who thought the original architect hadn't committed hard enough.

Lightning cracks behind the manor. The silhouette is briefly perfect — every turret, every gable, every grotesque ornament picked out in white against black sky.

You think: *This is a professional engagement. I have read cards at garden parties in Cheltenham. I have read for a bishop's wife. This is simply...an atmospheric venue.*

The carriage stops.

The door opens.

Rain falls. Somewhere behind you, something you cannot see makes a sound that is not thunder and is not wind and is not an animal you can name.

~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 1
~ blackthorn.things_rationalized += 1

+ [Step out. You're a professional.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Professional
+ [Hesitate. Something feels wrong.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Cautious
+ [Consider asking the driver to take you back.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Retreat

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Professional
You step out of the carriage. Your boots hit gravel. Rain hits your bonnet.

You are a professional.

A figure stands at the door. Tall. Skeletal. Holding a candelabra that does nothing useful in the rain but is clearly committed to the aesthetic.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}." His voice sounds like it last saw moisture during the Napoleonic Wars. "Lady Blackthorn is...expecting you."

He pauses on "expecting" in a way that makes you wonder if the word has a secondary meaning you're not aware of.

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1
~ blackthorn.composure += 1

+ [Follow him inside.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.MeetGraves

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Cautious
You step out slowly. Something about the manor makes your skin prickle — not dramatically, not like a penny dreadful, just...*wrong.* The way a room feels wrong when someone's been crying in it. The air is *thick.*

A figure stands at the door. Too tall, too thin, holding a candelabra that the rain is doing its best to extinguish.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}." His voice is dust and formality. "Lady Blackthorn is...expecting you."

Your instincts say: *pay attention.* You file the feeling away and straighten your bonnet.

~ blackthorn.house_influence += 1

+ [Follow him inside. Carefully.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.MeetGraves

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Arrival_Retreat
You consider it. Genuinely consider it. The rain, the gargoyles, the indefinable *sound* behind you—

The carriage is already moving.

The driver doesn't look back. His horse doesn't look back. The carriage rattles down the drive and into the dark as if it has a very pressing appointment somewhere that isn't here.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}."

You turn. A figure stands at the door. A walking anatomy lesson in a butler's uniform, holding a candelabra with the resigned air of a man who has seen guests try to flee before.

"Lady Blackthorn is... expecting you."

You don't have a choice. You never did, probably.

~ blackthorn.composure -= 1
~ blackthorn.house_influence += 1

+ [Follow him inside. It's not like you can leave.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.MeetGraves

:: Blackthorn.Session1.MeetGraves
"Mr. Graves, miss." He takes your carpetbag. His hand is very cold. "I shall show you to your room."

You follow him through the front doors.

The entrance hall is enormous. Marble floor, dark wood paneling, a chandelier that could comfortably seat six. Portraits line the walls — generations of Blackthorns in ascending order of Gothic intensity. The most recent one, at the far end, is a woman in black velvet who appears to have been painted during an eclipse.

"Mr. Graves." You try to sound conversational. "That's rather...on the nose. For a manor like this."

"The family has always valued thematic consistency, miss."

You can't tell if he's joking. His face doesn't seem to contain the necessary muscles.

You pass a portrait of a stern man in military dress. His painted eyes track you as you walk. You stop. Look back. The eyes are looking at you.

"Mr. Graves — did that painting just—"

"Yes, miss. They do that."

"...Right."

~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 1

+ [Rationalize it. Must be a trick of the candlelight.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Rationalize_Portraits
+ [Ask Mr. Graves directly how a painting can move its eyes.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ask_Graves
+ [Walk faster.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Walk_Faster

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Rationalize_Portraits
Candlelight. Obviously. The flames move, the shadows shift, the painted eyes appear to follow you. It's a well-documented optical phenomenon. Professor Crane mentions it in Chapter 12: "On the Atmospheric Enhancement of Reading Environments."

You're a rational person. From Bath.

~ blackthorn.things_rationalized += 1
~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1

+ [Keep walking. Sensibly.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ask_Graves
"Mr. Graves. How does a painting move its eyes?"

"I couldn't say, miss. It may be the candlelight."

"It's not the candlelight."

"No, miss. It isn't." He continues walking. "The third Lord Blackthorn commissioned the portraits from an artist of... unusual talent. The family was very pleased with the lifelike quality."

"The *lifelike* quality."

"Yes, miss. Will there be anything else?"

~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 1
~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1

+ [Continue to your room. At least you got a straight answer.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Walk_Faster
You walk faster. Mr. Graves matches your pace without appearing to increase his. His legs are very long. The corridor is very dark. The paintings are definitely, absolutely, without question watching you.

This is fine. This is a professional engagement.

~ blackthorn.composure -= 1

+ [Keep walking. Don't run. Professionals don't run.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom

# ============================================================================
# THE ROSE ROOM
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom
Mr. Graves opens a door on the second floor.

"The Rose Room, miss."

The room is vast. Four-poster bed with curtains heavy enough to muffle a cannon shot. Fireplace roaring — properly roaring, someone has fed it recently — but the room is cold. Not cold the way an old house is cold. Cold the way a room is cold when something in it *prefers* the cold.

Wallpaper: roses. Once red, now faded to the color of old blood. The window overlooks the moors — miles of heather and darkness and rain. The kind of view that makes you think "brooding" and then "exposure" and then "hypothermia."

Your carpetbag has been placed on the bed. You did not see Mr. Graves put it there.

"Why is it so cold?" you ask. "Despite the fire?"

"The previous occupant of this room. Miss Adelaide. She passed of consumption. 1847."

"I'm sorry to hear—"

"She still prefers it cold."

A beat.

"She... *still*—"

"Will you require extra blankets, miss?"

+ ["...Yes. Please. Several."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Blankets
+ ["Mr. Graves, are you telling me this room is haunted?"] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Haunted
+ ["I'd like a different room, please."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Different

:: Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Blankets
"At once, miss." He turns to leave. Pauses. "Dinner is at midnight."

"*Midnight?*"

"Lady Blackthorn prefers late hours. The household has adapted."

"That's...very late for dinner."

"Yes, miss." He closes the door.

You stand in the freezing room with the roaring fire and the watching wallpaper and the window that shows nothing but darkness and rain.

From somewhere in the house — far away, or maybe not as far as you'd like — a wolf howls.

You think: *What have I gotten myself into?*

From somewhere even further away — or maybe closer — a second howl. Higher-pitched. More... *dramatic.*

You think: *Why are there wolves in the house?*

+ [Unpack. Try to settle in.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Settle

:: Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Haunted
Mr. Graves pauses. He appears to consider the question with the gravity it deserves.

"The Rose Room has a resident, miss. Miss Adelaide does not trouble guests unless provoked. She merely prefers a colder temperature. I find it helpful to think of her as a... draft."

"A *draft.*"

"A persistent, localized, somewhat melancholy draft. Yes."

He hands you two extra blankets from the wardrobe — they were already prepared, as if this conversation was expected — and pauses at the door.

"Dinner is at midnight."

"Midnight. Of course it is."

He closes the door. From somewhere in the house, a wolf howls.

~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 1
~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1

+ [Settle in. A draft. Fine.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Settle

:: Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Different
"I'm afraid all other rooms are occupied, miss. The Rose Room is our finest guest accommodation."

"Even with the...draft?"

"Miss Adelaide is quite gentle. She merely lowers the temperature. She has not thrown anything in several years."

"*Thrown* anything—"

"Dinner is at midnight. Extra blankets are in the wardrobe."

He closes the door. You are alone. In a haunted room. In a Gothic manor. With wolves howling somewhere in the building.

You think: *Five pounds is not enough.*

~ blackthorn.composure -= 1
~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 1

+ [Lock the door. Unpack. Survive until morning.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Settle

:: Blackthorn.Session1.RoseRoom_Settle
You sit on the bed. The mattress is good, at least. The blankets are thick. The fire crackles and achieves absolutely nothing against the supernatural chill.

You open your carpetbag. Your tarot deck is there — warm, familiar, the one real thing in this dream that feels like yours. You hold it for a moment. The weight of it steadies you.

*The Complete Guide to Cartomancy* is there too. You open it to the chapter on "Reading in Unusual Circumstances." Professor Crane's advice: *"The competent cartomantist maintains her composure regardless of environment. Whether reading in a drawing room or a dungeon, the cards are the same. The reader is the same. The skill is the same."*

Thank you, Professor Crane. Very helpful. He did not, you notice, include a chapter on "What To Do When The Room Is Haunted And Dinner Is At Midnight And There Are Wolves."

You change into your reading dress — the gray wool, respectable, warm. Pin your hair. Check your reflection in the mirror above the washstand.

The mirror shows you.

Just you.

(You check twice. Just in case.)

You look at yourself. Mid-twenties. Brown hair, pinned sensibly. The face of a woman who reads cards for pocket money and has never in her life communed with the dead or gazed into the void or had a mystical experience more profound than correctly predicting that Mrs. Henderson's nephew would marry the wrong girl, which frankly anyone could have seen coming.

"You are from Bath," you tell your reflection. "You learned this from a book. You are here to work."

Your reflection agrees. It looks just as unconvinced as you feel.

The clock strikes midnight. Somewhere downstairs, a gong sounds.

+ [Go to dinner. Be professional.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Descent

# ============================================================================
# ACT 2: MIDNIGHT DINNER
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Descent
The corridors are darker now. Your candle throws jumping shadows. The portraits are definitely watching — you've stopped pretending they aren't.

You descend the main staircase. The dining room doors are open. Candlelight spills out — too many candles. Nobody needs this many candles. This is *decorative* fire.

You pause at the threshold.

The dining room is a stage set. Long table, dark wood, silver that catches the candlelight. Portraits of dead Blackthorns watching from the walls (their eyes move too). Rain against the tall windows. A chandelier that's doing its absolute best to be ominous.

The guests are already assembled.

+ [Enter] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Enter

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Enter
You enter. Every head turns.

At the head of the table: **Lady Blackthorn.**

She rises. Or rather, she *ascends* — there's no visible effort, she simply goes from seated to standing as if gravity is something she participates in voluntarily. Black velvet gown, widow's veil, skin so pale it's practically a statement of intent. She moves toward you and you're not entirely sure her feet touch the floor.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}. How *delightful.*"

She takes your hands. Hers are cold. Not Rose-Room cold — a different cold. The cold of marble. The cold of someone who has been indoors for a very long time.

"The cards told me you would come."

"I... responded to your advertisement in the *Times*, my lady."

"Did you? Or did *fate* respond for you?" She gives you a significant look. The look has italics.

"...I sent a telegram."

"The spirits work in mysterious ways." She guides you to the table. "Come. Sit. We've been *so* eager to meet our little card reader."

You are not little. You are a perfectly normal height. She is simply very tall and very dramatic and you are already quite tired of this.

"Dinner first," Lady Blackthorn announces to the table. "And then — a *séance.*"

"My lady, I should mention — I read tarot cards. I don't typically conduct séan—"

"Nonsense. You have *The Gift.* I can *sense* it."

"I have a *book.* From Hatchards. It cost three shillings."

"Such *modesty.*" She glides back to her seat. "Do wear something atmospheric for the séance."

"I'm wearing gray wool."

"How... *practical.*"

She says "practical" the way a duchess says "plague."

+ [Take your seat. Survey the room.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Survey

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Survey
@py:
# Track who player observes first — affects subtle relationship beats
blackthorn.dinner_survey_order = []
@endpy

You take your seat — midway down the table, between a chair that smells like wet dog and an empty chair that is much colder than its neighbors. The place settings include more forks than any meal could justify and a glass that appears to contain something very red.

The guests:

To Lady Blackthorn's right, a man in his early thirties stares at his wine glass as if it has personally wronged him. Dark circles under his eyes. Handsome in a haunted, exhausted way — the kind of face that would be quite appealing if it weren't so aggressively *miserable.* When thunder cracks outside, he flinches.

Across from you, a young woman in white — too white, deliberately white, *significally* white — keeps glancing at empty spaces in the room. Not at the walls or furniture. At the *air.* As if something's there.

At the far end, a man in his forties takes notes during the soup course. He has the intense, slightly wild-eyed look of someone who treats the world as a laboratory and everyone in it as a specimen. His pen scratches continuously.

And then there's the empty chair beside you. The one that smells like wet dog. And moor. And something expensively masculine and unnecessarily dramatic.

+ [Focus on the brooding man (Lord Ashford)] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Ashford
+ [Focus on the girl in white (Miss Arabella)] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Arabella
+ [Focus on the note-taker (Dr. Blackwood)] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Blackwood
+ [Ask about the empty chair] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Empty_Chair

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Ashford
~ blackthorn.dinner_survey_order.append("ashford")

Lady Blackthorn notices your attention. "Lord Ashford, you remember Miss {blackthorn.player_name}, our card reader?"

Lord Ashford looks up. His eyes are deep-set and troubled and he is doing absolutely nothing to disguise this. He has committed fully to anguish as a personality trait.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}. Forgive me. I am... distracted."

"Not at all, Lord Ashford. I hope you're—"

"The full moon approaches."

"...I'm sorry?"

Lady Blackthorn, smoothly: "Now, now. Let's not frighten our guest with talk of *family curses* before dessert."

You think: *Family curses. Of course. Why not.*

~ blackthorn.lord_ashford_trust += 1

@if "arabella" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the girl in white] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Arabella
@endif
@if "blackwood" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the note-taker] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Blackwood
@endif
@if "empty_chair" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Ask about the empty chair] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Empty_Chair
@endif
@if len(blackthorn.dinner_survey_order) >= 2:
    + [Continue dinner] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Arrives
@endif

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Arabella
~ blackthorn.dinner_survey_order.append("arabella")

The girl in white catches your eye. She's early twenties, ethereally beautiful in a way that seems rehearsed until you realize it isn't — she really is that pale, that delicate, that wide-eyed. She's been staring at a spot approximately two feet to the left of Dr. Blackwood's head for the last three minutes.

"Miss Grey, are you quite well?" you ask.

She startles. Turns to you. Her eyes are the lightest blue you've ever seen.

"Do you see them too?" she whispers.

"See... what?"

"The others. The ones who aren't really here anymore."

You look at the space she's been watching. You see air. Candlelight. A slightly suspicious stain on the wallpaper.

"I... I'm afraid I don't—"

She looks disappointed. Genuinely, vulnerably disappointed. "Oh. I thought you might. Being *sensitive* and all."

"I'm not particularly—"

Lady Blackthorn: "Arabella dear, don't monopolize our guest. She'll think we're *all* mad."

You think: *Too late.*

~ blackthorn.arabella_connection += 2

@if "ashford" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the brooding man] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Ashford
@endif
@if "blackwood" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the note-taker] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Blackwood
@endif
@if "empty_chair" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Ask about the empty chair] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Empty_Chair
@endif
@if len(blackthorn.dinner_survey_order) >= 2:
    + [Continue dinner] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Arrives
@endif

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Blackwood
~ blackthorn.dinner_survey_order.append("blackwood")

The note-taker notices you noticing him. He sets down his pen — reluctantly, the way an addict sets down a pipe — and fixes you with an evaluative stare.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}. You claim to read fortunes through cartomancy?"

"I read tarot cards, yes—"

"Fascinating." He does not sound fascinated. He sounds like he's filing you under a species heading. "Pure pareidolia, of course — the mind's tendency to impose patterns on random stimuli. Yet subjects consistently report *feeling* helped. I'm documenting the phenomenon."

"It's not random, exactly. The cards follow certain symbolic—"

"Confirmation bias. Selection bias. The Barnum effect." He ticks them off on his fingers. "I've written a paper on it. 'On the Persistence of Superstitious Belief Among the Otherwise Rational.' You are exhibit C."

"Exhibit—"

"Nothing personal. Exhibits A and B were a mesmerist and a phrenologist."

"Sir, has it occurred to you that pattern recognition is itself a valuable cognitive skill? You got your medical degree from a *book.* I got mine from a different one."

He blinks. Opens his mouth. Closes it. Opens it again.

"We shall discuss this further. I'd like to run *tests.*"

"I'd rather you didn't."

From a doorway you hadn't noticed, a dry female voice: "She's got you there, Doctor."

You turn. A woman in her thirties — elegant, sardonic, a lady's maid by her dress — stands with arms folded and an expression of pure, refined amusement.

**Miss Chen.** You don't know how you know her name, but you do. Guangzhou, originally. Been at the manor five years. Finds the "mysterious foreigner" tropes hilarious, given that everyone here is far more peculiar than she is.

"Miss Chen." Dr. Blackwood manages to sound simultaneously offended and impressed. "I don't recall inviting commentary from the staff."

"You didn't. I volunteered." She turns to you. "More wine, miss?"

"Please."

You become allies in that moment. Wordlessly and completely.

~ blackthorn.blackwood_respect += 1
~ blackthorn.chen_respect += 2

@if "ashford" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the brooding man] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Ashford
@endif
@if "arabella" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Turn your attention to the girl in white] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Meet_Arabella
@endif
@if "empty_chair" not in blackthorn.dinner_survey_order:
    + [Ask about the empty chair] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Empty_Chair
@endif
@if len(blackthorn.dinner_survey_order) >= 2:
    + [Continue dinner] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Arrives
@endif

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Empty_Chair
~ blackthorn.dinner_survey_order.append("empty_chair")

"Lady Blackthorn — the chair beside me. Are we expecting another guest?"

Lady Blackthorn's smile deepens. "Lord Ravencroft. He'll arrive... when the mood takes him."

"When the mood—"

"He has a *flair* for entrances. Best not to question it."

The chair smells powerfully of wet dog and moor grass and something that is either a very expensive cologne or the distilled essence of a Brontë novel.

Thomas — the footman, mid-twenties, cheerful face, the first person you've seen in this house who doesn't appear to be auditioning for something — appears at your elbow with a bread roll.

"Don't worry about Lord Ravencroft, miss," he says, quiet enough that Lady Blackthorn can't hear. "He's harmless. Mostly."

"Mostly?"

"He's very... *intense.* But the dog is lovely."

"The *dog*—"

Thomas opens his mouth to explain, but at that precise moment, every candle in the room flickers.

~ blackthorn.thomas_friendliness += 1

+ [Continue dinner] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Arrives

# ============================================================================
# THE ENTRANCE
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Arrives
The doors burst open.

There is wind. Where is the wind coming from? You are *inside.* There is no reason for wind. And yet: wind. Enough to make the candles gutter and the curtains billow and your napkin to lift delicately from your lap and settle on the floor.

A figure stands in the doorway.

Tall. Dark hair wild and windswept — from the *indoor wind,* apparently. Billowing white shirt open at the collar. Why is his shirt billowing? There is no wind IN THE HALLWAY. The wind appears to be localized exclusively around his person, like a personal weather system committed to drama.

His eyes burn with intensity. This is not a metaphor. They are genuinely, aggressively intense. They are eyes that have read too much Byron and taken it personally.

At his side: a dog.

Not a dog. A *borzoi.* Enormous, elegant, long-snouted, with flowing silver-white fur and the exact same wild, windswept aesthetic as its owner. They stand together in the doorway and they look — there is no other word for this — *disturbingly similar.* Same long, elegant face. Same intense gaze. Same hair situation.

It is one of those dog-and-owner situations. The dog-and-owner situation to end all dog-and-owner situations.

**Lord Ravencroft** strides to the table.

He **points** at you.

"*YOU.*"

Everyone turns to stare.

"...Me?"

"Yes. *YOU.* I saw you arrive. From my window. On the moors. Where I was *BROODING.*"

"...Right."

"You have... a *QUALITY.*"

"I have a *job,* sir. I'm the card reader."

"The *CARDS.* Yes. You commune with FORCES BEYOND—"

"I read from a *book*—"

"I *MUST* have a reading. My *SOUL* is in *TORMENT*—"

Lady Blackthorn, with the tone of someone managing a recurring situation: "Ravencroft, *darling,* do sit down. You're frightening Miss {blackthorn.player_name}."

Lord Ravencroft sits. In the chair beside you. The one that smells like moor and dog and drama.

He does not break eye contact.

The borzoi sits too. At his feet. It also does not break eye contact. The dog is staring at you with the same burning intensity as its master and you are being double-stared-at by a man and his dog and this is your life now.

"This is Heathsniff," Lord Ravencroft says.

"...*Heathsniff.*"

"He is my *SOUL COMPANION.* We roam the moors together. He understands my *TORMENT.*"

Heathsniff: still staring.

Lord Ravencroft: still staring.

You: eating soup, deeply uncomfortable.

+ ["That's... a very literary name for a dog."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Literary
+ [Ignore him. Focus on your soup.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Ignore
+ [Look to the servants for help.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Help

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Literary
"A literary name for a *literary soul,*" he says, somehow making this sound like a profound philosophical statement rather than a description of a dog.

Miss Chen, pouring wine, catches your eye. Her expression says: *welcome to my life.*

Thomas, serving the fish course, leans down as he places your plate. "The dog's actually quite friendly, miss. It's the master you want to watch."

Lord Ravencroft: "Thomas."

Thomas: "More wine, m'lord?"

~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 1
~ blackthorn.heathsniff_affection += 1

+ [Eat your dinner. Ignore the staring.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Servants

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Ignore
You focus on your soup with the concentration of a woman who has decided that Lord Ravencroft and his matching dog do not exist. Your soup is very interesting. Possibly the most interesting soup you've ever encountered. You could write a monograph on this soup.

Lord Ravencroft does not appear to notice that he's being ignored. Or he notices and finds it *thrilling.*

"The moors were WILD tonight," he says to no one and everyone. "Heathsniff and I rode until the STARS themselves TREMBLED—"

Miss Chen, dryly, from behind Lady Blackthorn's chair: "There are no stars, Lord Ravencroft. It's been raining for three days."

"The *METAPHORICAL* stars—"

"Of course."

~ blackthorn.composure += 1
~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1

+ [Focus on the soup. The soup is normal. You like the soup.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Servants

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ravencroft_Help
You look desperately at the nearest servant.

Mrs. Winters is already there.

She has materialized at your elbow — a woman in her sixties, warm eyes, the particular solidity of someone who has seen every conceivable form of aristocratic nonsense and has developed a permanent, load-bearing exasperation.

"Don't mind them, dear," she says, quietly, as she refills your water glass. "They're all quite mad."

"*Thank you,*" you whisper.

"More soup?"

"Please. Yes. Anything."

She pats your shoulder — briefly, professionally, but with genuine warmth. "You're doing fine. Just read the cards like normal. Try not to engage with Lord Ravencroft's dramatics."

"He's very... *intense.*"

"That's one word for it."

~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 2
~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 1

+ [Accept the soup. And the solidarity.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Servants

# ============================================================================
# THE SERVANTS (The Only Sane People Here)
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_Servants
The dinner progresses. The food is good — someone in this house can cook, and that someone is probably not supernatural. Between courses, the servants orbit the table like planets around a collapsing star.

**Mrs. Winters** — housekeeper, sixties, the quiet authority of a woman who has served three mistresses, survived six housemaids, and long ago stopped being surprised by anything. She moves through the room with the ease of someone who knows every creaking board and exactly which doors to avoid after dark. When she serves you, she gives you looks that communicate entire paragraphs. The current paragraph is: *Eat your food. Ignore the aristocrats. I'll get you through this.*

**Thomas** — footman, mid-twenties, irrepressibly cheerful in a way that seems heroic given his workplace. He winks at you when he pours your wine. He is the first person in this house who has made you feel like the situation might be survivable.

When he serves Lord Ashford, he does so with the practiced ease of someone managing a complicated animal. "More wine, m'lord? Shall I draw the curtains? The moon isn't visible tonight — the clouds, sir." The way he says it suggests the moon's visibility is a nightly concern.

**Miss Chen** — lady's maid, thirties, from Guangzhou, elegant and sardonic in equal measure. She attends Lady Blackthorn with the brisk efficiency of someone who considers the job entertaining enough to compensate for the considerable drawbacks. You catch her watching you during dessert with an expression of genuine curiosity — she's evaluating you, and her evaluation standards are high.

Between the fish and the pudding, you find a moment.

+ ["Do you three... live here?"] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Servants_Chat
+ [Focus on observing the gentry instead] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Gentry_Observe

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Servants_Chat
All three servants are within earshot. Something about the question makes them exchange a look — the look of people who have been asked this before and have developed a coordinated response.

"Unfortunately," all three say, nearly in unison.

Mrs. Winters: "Been here forty years."

Thomas: "Two years for me."

Miss Chen: "Five years. I keep meaning to leave but the pay is good and the dramatics are entertaining."

"Are they... *always* like this?"

All three: "Always."

Thomas: "The trick is to just be very matter-of-fact about everything. 'Yes, m'lord, I'll fetch your tea. Yes, m'lord, I see you've turned into a wolf again. I'll draw the curtains.'"

"...Did you say *wolf?*"

Thomas: "You'll see. Full moon's in three days."

"I'm sorry, *what*—"

Lady Blackthorn, from the head of the table: "Thomas, that's *quite* enough."

Mrs. Winters, gathering plates: "Last card reader lasted two days before fleeing in the night."

"That's... not reassuring."

"Wasn't meant to be, dear. More pudding?"

~ blackthorn.servant_trust += 2
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 1
~ blackthorn.thomas_friendliness += 1
~ blackthorn.chen_respect += 1

+ [Finish dinner. Brace yourself for what comes next.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_End

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Gentry_Observe
You watch the gentry instead.

Lord Ashford barely eats. He pushes food around his plate and stares at the rain against the windows with the expression of a man waiting for a verdict.

Miss Arabella eats neatly, primly, and keeps flinching at things you can't see. At one point she whispers "excuse me" to the empty air beside her plate. No one else reacts.

Dr. Blackwood eats with one hand and takes notes with the other. You catch a fragment of what he's writing: *"Subject C (card reader) displays defensive rationalization patterns consistent with—"* He sees you looking and angles the notebook away.

Lord Ravencroft eats nothing. He drinks wine and stares at you. Heathsniff, lying under the table, has placed his enormous head on your foot. You don't remember this happening. It's just a fact of your existence now. A borzoi is on your foot.

Lady Blackthorn presides. She doesn't eat either — her plate contains something very red that she occasionally stirs but never lifts to her mouth. You file this away under "things you're going to think about later when you're safely in Bath."

~ blackthorn.house_influence += 1
~ reader.insight += 1

+ [File it all away. The pudding is cleared.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_End

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Dinner_End
The pudding is cleared. Lady Blackthorn rises.

"Now then." She clasps her hands. The candlelight does something theatrical with her cheekbones. "Shall we retire to the parlor? It is time to contact the *spirit realm.*"

"My lady, I really should clarify — I read tarot cards. I don't *commune* with spirits—"

"But you have *The Gift.*"

"I have a *book*—"

"Come now. Don't be modest." She gestures to the party. "Everyone, please. The parlor."

They rise. Lord Ashford with reluctance. Miss Arabella with nervous excitement. Dr. Blackwood with his notebook already open. Lord Ravencroft with the fluid grace of a man who has practiced standing up from dinner tables in a mirror.

Heathsniff removes his head from your foot. Stands. Stretches. Shakes his flowing fur. He does this with the deliberate elegance of a creature who knows exactly how good he looks.

Mrs. Winters appears at your elbow one final time.

"You'll be fine, dear," she says. "Just read the cards like you always do."

"Mrs. Winters, they want me to conduct a *séance.* I don't *do* séances."

"I know, dear. But it's that kind of house."

She squeezes your arm — once, brief, warm — and goes to clear the table.

You follow the party to the parlor.

You are from Bath.

You learned this from a book.

Whatever is about to happen, that hasn't changed.

+ [Enter the parlor] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Setup

# ============================================================================
# END OF PART 1
# ============================================================================
# Part 2 continues with:
#   - The séance setup and card draw
#   - Lord Blackthorn's ghost appears (undeniable supernatural)
#   - Card interpretations (grounded/diplomatic/gothic/panicked)
#   - Post-séance Ravencroft hallway encounter
#   - Mrs. Winters rescue
