# ============================================================================

# ============================================================================
# ACT 3: THE SÉANCE
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Setup
The parlor.

Someone has been busy. Too many candles — every surface holds at least three. Heavy curtains drawn against the rain. A round table at the center, covered in black cloth. Chairs arranged in a circle. The whole room smells like beeswax and anticipation and something underneath those things that you can't name and don't want to.

There is a ouija board on a side table. You are not going anywhere near it.

"Please, everyone. Sit." Lady Blackthorn takes her place at the table. Her hands are very white against the black cloth.

They sit.

Lord Ashford: troubled, resigned, like a man who has attended séances before and found them wanting.

Miss Arabella: nervous but *excited,* eyes flickering to the empty spaces in the room with an expression that is less "I see dead people" and more "the dead people are being really chatty tonight."

Dr. Blackwood: notebook open, pen poised. He has already written the heading: *"Séance Observation Notes, 14th October 1873."* He has underlined it twice.

Lord Ravencroft: *staring at you.* He has not stopped staring at you since he arrived. He has simply relocated the staring from the dining room to the parlor.

Heathsniff: lying at Ravencroft's feet. Also staring at you. The two of them are like a Renaissance painting of devotion, except the devotion is aimed at a woman from Bath who wants to go home.

The empty chair. Across from you. For the "guest."

Lady Blackthorn places her hands flat on the table. "We gather to contact my late husband, Lord Desmond Blackthorn. Who departed this mortal realm five years ago under... *mysterious circumstances.*"

"I'm very sorry for your loss—"

"Are you?" She gives you a look. The look has footnotes.

"...Yes?"

"He was a *terrible* husband. Absolutely dreadful. I'm *delighted* he's dead."

Everyone around the table nods as if this is a perfectly normal thing to say at a séance for the man in question.

"But I need to know where he hid the *money.*"

More nodding.

You think: *I want to go home.*

Lady Blackthorn turns to you. "Miss {blackthorn.player_name}, please... *open the veil.*"

+ ["I don't know how to 'open the veil.' I read tarot cards."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Resist
+ ["I can lay cards for your late husband. That's what I do."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Redirect
+ [Say nothing. Pull out your deck. Just do your job.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Silent

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Resist
"I don't know how to 'open the veil.' I read tarot cards. From a book. I have never opened, closed, or in any way adjusted a veil in my professional career."

Arabella, helpfully: "Just ask the spirits to come through!"

"I really don't think—"

Dr. Blackwood, scribbling: "Fascinating. The subject is uncomfortable with the role she's being forced into. Note the defensive posture, the repeated invocation of her training manual—"

"I'm not a *subject*—"

Ravencroft, with the intensity of a man ordering his final meal: "Do you *fear* what you might see beyond the veil?"

"I fear being held responsible for things I can't actually *do*—"

Lady Blackthorn: "Just draw some cards, dear. For *atmosphere.*"

You look around the table. Every face is turned to you. Even Heathsniff.

You sigh.

"*Fine.*"

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 2
~ blackthorn.composure -= 1

+ [Pull out your deck.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_CardDraw

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Redirect
"I can lay a spread for your late husband. Cards for the departed — there's a chapter on it in my book. It won't *summon* anyone, but it can tell us something about who he was, what he left unfinished, what's hidden."

Lady Blackthorn looks mildly disappointed that you're not going to levitate or speak in tongues, but she waves a hand. "Very well. Your methods. Whatever works."

You think: *My methods work fine, thank you. They involve a deck of cards and pattern recognition and absolutely no ghosts.*

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion -= 1

+ [Set up the spread. Your way.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_CardDraw

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Silent
You say nothing. You pull your deck from the pocket of your dress — you've been keeping it close all evening without quite knowing why — and set it on the black cloth.

The table goes quiet.

There's something about the gesture. A professional pulling out her tools. The levity drops. Even Dr. Blackwood's pen pauses.

Ravencroft leans forward. "She's *doing* it. She's opening the—"

"I'm shuffling cards, Lord Ravencroft. Please don't narrate."

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1
~ blackthorn.composure += 1
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion += 1

+ [Shuffle. Let the silence do its work.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_CardDraw

# ============================================================================
# THE CARD DRAW
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_CardDraw
@py:
# Card pools — "Through the Veil" spread
# 5 positions, 3 possible cards each
# Reversal chance: 25% (Gothic volatility)

position_1_deck = Deck(cards=["King of Swords", "The Emperor", "Knight of Pentacles"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_2_deck = Deck(cards=["Seven of Swords", "Five of Pentacles", "Page of Cups"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_3_deck = Deck(cards=["Ten of Pentacles", "Four of Pentacles", "Six of Swords"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_4_deck = Deck(cards=["The Moon", "The High Priestess", "Eight of Swords"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])
position_5_deck = Deck(cards=["Three of Swords", "Justice", "Judgement"], reversals=[0.25, 0.25, 0.25])

reading = Reading(spread_id="through-the-veil", decks=[
    position_1_deck,
    position_2_deck,
    position_3_deck,
    position_4_deck,
    position_5_deck
])

cards = reading.draw_cards()
@endpy

You shuffle. The sound is loud in the quiet room — the soft riffle and snap of pasteboard, the only normal sound in a deeply abnormal situation.

"This spread is called 'Through the Veil,'" you say. Professor Crane, Chapter 14. You've done this three times before, at estate readings in Cheltenham, and nothing happened except some satisfied widows and reasonable tips. "Five cards. Five questions about the departed."

You lay them face down on the black cloth.

"The Departed — who they were in life. Their Message — what they wish to communicate. What They Left Behind. What's Hidden. And the Truth."

Your hands are steady. You're a professional. You've done this before.

You turn the first card.

**Position 1: The Departed**
**{cards[0].name}**{cards[0].reversed ?  — Reversed | }

The moment it touches the table—

The candles flicker.

Not gently. Not the way candles flicker in a draft. Every candle in the room dims to a blue point and then flares back, and the temperature drops so sharply you can see your breath.

"What—"

A VOICE. From nowhere. From everywhere. From the empty chair across the table.

**"WHO SUMMONS ME?"**

Everyone jumps. Dr. Blackwood's pen leaves a streak of ink across his notebook. Lord Ashford's hand goes to the table. Miss Arabella claps both hands over her mouth — not in surprise but in *recognition.* As if she's been seeing him all along and is simply relieved everyone else can see him now.

Lord Ravencroft stands. His chair falls backward. Heathsniff howls — one long, eerie, beautiful note.

You: standing, hands flat on the table, cards forgotten: "I didn't— I just laid down a *card*—"

**"WHO DARES DISTURB MY REST?"**

A figure materializes in the empty chair. Translucent. Glowing faintly, the cold blue-white of moonlight on snow. A man. Heavy-set, imperious, dressed in the fashion of five years ago — or five centuries ago, or both. He is dead. He is here. He is looking at you with the absolute fury of someone who has been rudely awakened.

**Lord Desmond Blackthorn's Ghost** sits at his own séance table and he is *angry.*

~ blackthorn.supernatural_encounters += 5
~ blackthorn.ghost_encountered = True
~ blackthorn.composure -= 3

"*VICTORIA.*" The ghost turns to Lady Blackthorn. "I should have known."

Lady Blackthorn: "Hello, Desmond. You're looking well. For a corpse."

"You *KILLED* me—"

"You tried to *stake* me first. And you missed. Which was typical."

"*WHO IS THIS MORTAL?*" The ghost rounds on you. "*WHY DOES SHE CARRY THE CARDS?*"

+ ["I— I learned from a BOOK—"] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Panicked
+ ["I'm a card reader, sir. Hired for the weekend. Five pounds."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Grounded
+ ["I am Miss {blackthorn.player_name}, of Bath, and I am just as surprised as you are."] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Honest

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Panicked
"I— I learned from a *BOOK*—"

"*SHE HAS NO POWER. SHE IS BUT MUNDANE FLESH.*"

"*THAT'S WHAT I'VE BEEN SAYING—*"

Your voice is higher than you'd like. Your hands are shaking. There is a ghost. At the table. A real ghost. You have read cards at garden parties in Cheltenham and nothing like this has ever happened and your book did not include a chapter on this and you are from *BATH*—

Mrs. Winters, from the doorway, steady as bedrock: "Pull yourself together, dear. You're doing fine."

"Mrs. Winters, there's a *GHOST*—"

"Yes, dear. There usually is. Tea?"

~ blackthorn.composure -= 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['panicked'] += 1
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 1

+ [Drink the tea. Read the cards. Somehow.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Continue

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Grounded
"I'm a card reader, sir. Hired for the weekend. Five pounds. I read tarot cards. I did not summon you and I don't know how you're here, but I assure you, my cards are from a shop in Bath and they have never done anything like this before."

The ghost pauses. He appears to have expected groveling or screaming or mystic incantations. He was not expecting a job description.

"*YOU... READ CARDS. FOR MONEY.*"

"For a living, yes. It's a skill. Like accounting, but with better artwork."

A beat. From behind you, the faintest sound — Mrs. Winters, in the doorway, exhaling. Not quite a laugh. Approval.

"*SHE HAS NO POWER,*" the ghost says, but with less conviction. "*SHE IS BUT MUNDANE FLESH.*"

"That's what I've been *saying,* sir."

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 3
~ blackthorn.composure += 1
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['grounded'] += 1
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 2

+ [Sit down. Read the cards. It's what you're paid for.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Continue

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Honest
"I am Miss {blackthorn.player_name}, of Bath, and I am just as surprised as you are. I laid down a card and you... arrived. This has never happened before. I don't understand it. But I'm here and you're here and I have cards on the table, so perhaps we should just... proceed?"

You're surprised by how steady your voice sounds. It doesn't match the way your legs feel.

The ghost stares at you. Something shifts in his translucent expression — not softening, exactly, but a recalibration. He expected a mystic. You're a professional having a very unusual day at work.

"*HMPH.*" He settles in the chair. The chair creaks, which shouldn't be possible. "*VERY WELL. PROCEED.*"

From the doorway, Mrs. Winters nods. Once. Firmly.

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 2
~ blackthorn.composure += 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['grounded'] += 1
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 2
~ blackthorn.lord_ashford_trust += 1

+ [Sit down. Begin the reading.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Continue

# ============================================================================
# THE READING (With Ghost Present)
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Ghost_Continue
You sit back down. Your hands are shaking. You clasp them together under the table until they stop.

There is a ghost at the table. An actual, genuine, undeniable ghost. The portraits were one thing — you could rationalize moving eyes. The cold room was one thing — old houses are cold. But this is a *dead man* sitting in a *chair* and he is *talking* and your book did not prepare you for this.

Mrs. Winters appears with a cup of tea. She sets it next to your elbow. "You're doing fine, dear. Just read the cards like always."

You pick up the tea. Drink. It's hot and strong and sweet — too sweet, Mrs. Winters has put sugar in it, the kind of sugar you give someone after a shock — and it steadies you.

"Right." You set down the cup. Look at the spread. "Right."

The first card is already face-up.

@render render_reading(reading=reading, highlight=0)

**Position 1: The Departed — {cards[0].name}**{cards[0].reversed ?  (Reversed) | }

You know this card. You've read it a hundred times in warm, well-lit drawing rooms for perfectly alive people. You know what it means. The fact that you're reading it for a *ghost* doesn't change the meaning. The cards are the same. The reader is the same. The skill is the same.

*Thank you, Professor Crane.*

You turn the remaining cards, one by one. Each one lands on the table and the ghost flickers — brighter, angrier, colder — as the picture emerges.

**Position 2: Their Message — {cards[1].name}**{cards[1].reversed ?  (Reversed) | }
**Position 3: What They Left Behind — {cards[2].name}**{cards[2].reversed ?  (Reversed) | }
**Position 4: What's Hidden — {cards[3].name}**{cards[3].reversed ?  (Reversed) | }
**Position 5: The Truth — {cards[4].name}**{cards[4].reversed ?  (Reversed) | }

The spread is complete. Five cards on black cloth, lit by blue-tinged candlelight, with a ghost's cold glow washing over them.

You study them.

You *know* what they say.

+ [Read them honestly. The same way you'd read for anyone.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Grounded
+ [Soften the truth. The ghost is right there and he looks angry.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Diplomatic
+ [Lean into the drama. Give them the séance they wanted.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Gothic
+ [You're too shaken. Just get through it.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Panicked

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Grounded
You steady yourself. You are from Bath. You read cards for a living. This is a reading. It doesn't matter that the subject is dead and present and glowing. The cards are the cards.

"The spread tells a fairly clear story."

You point to Position 1.

@if cards[0].name == "King of Swords":
    "The King of Swords{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed |  } in the Departed position. This represents who your late husband was in life." You look at the ghost. He glares back. "{cards[0].reversed ? Reversed, this is a man who used his intelligence to deceive. Sharp-minded, yes, but that sharpness was turned to dishonest purposes | A man of sharp intellect and authority. But in this context — given the other cards — that intellect was used for calculation, not justice}."
@elif cards[0].name == "The Emperor":
    "The Emperor{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed |  } in the Departed position. {cards[0].reversed ? An Emperor reversed is authority that has become tyranny. Control that became corruption. Your husband ruled this estate like a kingdom, and he ruled it badly | The Emperor. A man of structure and authority. He controlled things — the estate, the finances, the household. But control isn't the same as honesty}."
@else:
    "The Knight of Pentacles{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed |  } in the Departed position. {cards[0].reversed ? Reversed, this knight's diligence became obsession. He was methodical, yes — methodically *extracting* from everything around him | A practical man. Methodical. Focused on material wealth. But the cards around him suggest that focus became something darker}."
@endif

The ghost flickers. "*SLANDER—*"

"It's not slander if the cards say it, sir. And they do."

Lady Blackthorn, with evident satisfaction: "Go on."

You move to Positions 2 and 3.

@if cards[1].name == "Seven of Swords":
    "The Seven of Swords as his message. {cards[1].reversed ? Reversed, this suggests secrets coming to light — things he took that are being uncovered | This card is about deception. Theft. Taking what isn't yours and hoping no one notices}."
@elif cards[1].name == "Five of Pentacles":
    "The Five of Pentacles as his message. {cards[1].reversed ? Reversed — hardship ending, resources being recovered | Poverty. Loss. But not *his* poverty — he created it. In others. The estate, the tenants, anyone who depended on his management}."
@else:
    "The Page of Cups as his message. {cards[1].reversed ? Reversed — an emotional message that's been blocked or corrupted | An emotional offering. But in this spread, alongside these other cards... it reads as manipulation. Using feeling as currency}."
@endif

@if cards[2].name == "Ten of Pentacles":
    "And what he left behind: the Ten of Pentacles{cards[2].reversed ?  reversed | }. {cards[2].reversed ? An inheritance in ruins. The estate's finances — they're worse than you know, Lady Blackthorn. He didn't just mismanage. He *dismantled* | The legacy of wealth. But the question is where it *went.* This card suggests the money exists — it's just not where it should be}."
@elif cards[2].name == "Four of Pentacles":
    "What he left behind: the Four of Pentacles{cards[2].reversed ?  reversed | }. {cards[2].reversed ? Reversed — the grip has loosened. Whatever he was hoarding, it can be found now | He was hoarding. Clutching resources. Hiding them away. Not spending and not sharing — just *keeping*}."
@else:
    "What he left behind: the Six of Swords{cards[2].reversed ?  reversed | }. {cards[2].reversed ? A journey that was never completed. Unfinished business — literally | Transition. Departure. He was moving things — money, assets, something — out of the estate. Somewhere else. Somewhere hidden}."
@endif

The ghost is *furious* now. His glow has intensified. The room is frigid. Frost is forming on the windowpanes.

"*I DID WHAT I HAD TO—*"

"The cards disagree, sir."

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 3
~ blackthorn.composure += 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['grounded'] += 2
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion += 2
~ blackthorn.lord_ashford_trust += 2
~ blackthorn.arabella_connection += 1

+ [Turn to the last two cards. The ones that matter.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Hidden

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Diplomatic
You look at the cards. You look at the ghost. You look at Lady Blackthorn, who is watching you with the focused attention of a woman who wants her money found.

You choose your words carefully.

"The cards paint a *complex* picture."

You gesture to Position 1.

@if cards[0].name == "King of Swords":
    "The King of Swords{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed | }. Your husband was intelligent — *very* intelligent. {cards[0].reversed ? But the reversal suggests that intelligence was... not always used transparently | But intelligence without transparency can lead to... complications}."
@elif cards[0].name == "The Emperor":
    "The Emperor{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed | }. A man of authority and control. {cards[0].reversed ? Reversed, this suggests that control became somewhat... excessive | An estate like this requires a firm hand. Perhaps too firm}."
@else:
    "The Knight of Pentacles{cards[0].reversed ?  reversed | }. A practical, methodical man. {cards[0].reversed ? Though the reversal implies that practicality shaded into something less admirable | Focused on material concerns — perhaps to the exclusion of other values}."
@endif

The ghost glowers but doesn't scream. You're threading a needle between truth and tact.

"The middle cards suggest... financial irregularities." You don't use the word "theft." You say "irregularities" as if you're an accountant rather than a card reader sitting across from a dead man. "Resources that were redirected. An estate whose accounts don't quite... balance."

Lady Blackthorn: "I *knew* it. Where did he put it?"

"I'm getting there, my lady."

The ghost: "*YOU UNDERSTAND NOTHING—*"

"I understand your wife wants her money back, sir. The cards are being quite clear about that."

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1
~ blackthorn.composure += 1
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['diplomatic'] += 2
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion += 1
~ blackthorn.blackwood_respect += 1

+ [Move to the final two cards.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Hidden

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Gothic
Something in you shifts. Maybe it's the candles. Maybe it's the ghost. Maybe it's the black cloth and the rain against the windows and the terrible, wonderful, ridiculous *atmosphere* of this room. Whatever it is, a part of you that isn't from Bath — a part that might have been *waiting* for this — leans into it.

"The *spirits* are troubled."

Your voice drops. It sounds different. More resonant. More... *atmospheric.*

"The cards reveal a *darkness.* A soul *stained* by avarice. The departed carries *secrets* beyond the veil — secrets that *weigh* on the living and the dead alike."

Lady Blackthorn: *delighted.* "Yes! YES! This is what I was hoping for!"

Dr. Blackwood, scribbling furiously: "Note the shift in vocal register — subject is adopting performative cadence consistent with —"

Miss Arabella clasps her hands: "She's *channeling.*"

Ravencroft: "*Magnificent.*"

You are not channeling. You are *performing.* And a small, honest part of you knows it — knows that you're giving them the show they wanted instead of the reading they need. The cards would tell you the same thing in plain English. But the room wanted Gothic, so Gothic is what you're giving them.

The ghost stares at you with something you hadn't expected: *contempt.*

"*SHE PLAYS AT POWER SHE DOES NOT HAVE.*"

That stings. Because he's right.

~ blackthorn.gothic_persona += 3
~ blackthorn.groundedness -= 2
~ blackthorn.house_influence += 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['gothic'] += 2
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion += 3
~ blackthorn.winters_approval -= 2

+ [Press on. The final cards await.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Hidden

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Read_Panicked
Your hands won't stop shaking. You look at the cards and you know what they mean — you *always* know what they mean, you've been doing this for three years — but between your knowledge and your mouth is a ghost, an actual ghost, and he's looking at you and he's *dead* and your book didn't cover this and you can't—

"The— the first card. It's the— it represents—" Your voice sounds thin. Wrong. Like someone else speaking through you.

You try to focus. King of Swords. Emperor. Knight of Pentacles. You know what it means. You've read this card a hundred times. But a hundred times without a dead man sitting across from you glowing blue and your hands shaking so badly the tea in the cup is making little waves—

"I— I'm sorry—"

Arabella, gently: "Take your time."

Dr. Blackwood: scribbling "Subject displaying acute stress response—"

"I am NOT a *subject,* Dr. Blackwood—"

The ghost: "*THE MORTAL CANNOT EVEN SPEAK. WHY IS SHE HERE.*"

That does it. Something in you — something stubborn, something from Bath — snaps.

"I am *here,* sir, because your wife *hired* me, and I am doing my *best* under circumstances that were *not in the advertisement.*"

Not a great reading. But at least you're standing.

~ blackthorn.composure -= 3
~ blackthorn.groundedness -= 1
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['panicked'] += 2
~ blackthorn.arabella_connection += 1

+ [Two cards left. Finish this.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Hidden

# ============================================================================
# THE HIDDEN CARDS AND THE TRUTH
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Hidden
You move to the final two cards. These are the ones that matter — What's Hidden and The Truth.

Position 4.

@if cards[3].name == "The Moon":
    "The Moon. Secrets. Deception. False appearances." You look at the ghost. "You hid things. Not just money. *Yourself.* The Moon says that nobody in this household knew who you really were."

    The ghost's glow dims. Not anger — something else. Something that might be, in a dead man, shame.
@elif cards[3].name == "The High Priestess":
    "The High Priestess. Hidden knowledge. Things concealed behind a veil." You almost laugh — given the circumstances. "You had secrets, Lord Blackthorn. Secrets you carried beyond death. Things you made sure nobody could find."

    The ghost shifts in his chair. The translucent face is unreadable.
@else:
    "The Eight of Swords. Imprisonment. Someone trapped by lies and unable to escape them." You pause. "This isn't just about you, is it? You trapped *others* in your web. People who depended on this estate — who couldn't leave because you'd made them complicit."

    The ghost flickers violently. You've touched something.
@endif

The room is very cold now. Your breath fogs. Lady Blackthorn's wine glass has frost on the rim.

"*ENOUGH,*" the ghost snarls. "*YOU KNOW NOTHING—*"

"One card left."

You turn Position 5.

**The Truth.**

@if cards[4].name == "Three of Swords":
    The Three of Swords.

    Three swords through a heart. Rain. Grief. Betrayal that cuts to the center of everything.

    The ghost sees it and *recoils.*
@elif cards[4].name == "Justice":
    Justice.

    A figure on a throne. Scales in one hand, sword in the other. Perfect balance. Perfect consequence.

    The card *glows.*

    Not candlelight. Not reflection. The card itself — the printed image on its face — is luminous. Warm gold against the blue-white cold of the ghost.

    ~ blackthorn.cards_glowed = True
@else:
    Judgement.

    The angel's trumpet. The dead rising. The final accounting.

    The ghost stares at it. Something in his translucent face changes — the fury collapses into something older and more terrible.
@endif

+ [Deliver the truth plainly. No drama. Just the cards.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Grounded
+ [Deliver it firmly but not cruelly.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Diplomatic
+ [Let the moment take you. This is bigger than Bath.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Gothic
+ [You can barely speak. But you speak.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Shaken

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Grounded
"The truth."

Your voice is steady. You don't know how. The ghost is glowing and the room is freezing and your tea has gone cold in the cup, but your voice is steady.

@if cards[4].name == "Three of Swords":
    "The Three of Swords. Betrayal. You stole from this estate, Lord Blackthorn. From your wife, your household, the people who depended on you. And the betrayal wasn't just financial — you hurt someone deeply. Someone who trusted you."
@elif cards[4].name == "Justice":
    "Justice. Accounts must be settled. Debts must be paid." You meet the ghost's eyes — translucent, furious, and for the first time, *afraid.* "You stole from this estate and hid the evidence, and this card says it doesn't matter that you're dead. The debt remains."
@else:
    "Judgement. The final reckoning. You're being called to account, Lord Blackthorn. Not by me — by the cards, by the house, by whatever it is that brought you here tonight. The truth about what you did is going to come out. It's coming out *now.*"
@endif

The ghost SCREAMS.

Not a word. A sound. The sound a dead man makes when the thing he hid behind his life's work is laid bare on a table by a woman from Bath with a three-shilling book.

@if blackthorn.cards_glowed:
    The Justice card blazes. The glow fills the room — warm gold overwhelming cold blue — and the ghost's form *buckles.*
@endif

"*THE LIBRARY,*" the ghost gasps. He's fading. Being pulled back. "*BEHIND THE BYRON COLLECTION. I HID IT ALL— THE ACCOUNTS, THE DEEDS, EVERYTHING—*"

He looks at you. One last moment. Dead eyes meeting living ones.

"*The cards... they see true. Even beyond the veil.*"

He vanishes.

The candles flare back to normal. The temperature rises. The frost on Lady Blackthorn's wine glass melts and runs down the stem.

Silence.

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 3
~ blackthorn.composure += 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['grounded'] += 2
~ blackthorn.money_location_revealed = True
~ blackthorn.servant_trust += 2
~ reader.competence += 1

+ [The séance is over. The room exhales.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Aftermath

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Diplomatic
"The final card tells us what we need to know."

You're measured. Careful. The ghost is clearly distressed and you're not cruel, even to the dead.

@if cards[4].name == "Three of Swords":
    "The Three of Swords. There was a betrayal. A significant one. Lord Blackthorn, the cards suggest that the estate's finances were... deliberately mismanaged. And someone was hurt by it — not just financially."
@elif cards[4].name == "Justice":
    "Justice. This card means *balance.* Things that were taken must be returned. Debts incurred must be repaid." You soften your voice, just slightly. "Lord Blackthorn, whatever you did — and the cards are quite clear that you *did* something — the reckoning has arrived."
@else:
    "Judgement. The accounting. This card says it's time for the truth, Lord Blackthorn. Not as punishment — as *resolution.* Whatever you hid, it wants to be found. Surely even you must be tired of carrying it."
@endif

The ghost shudders. Not a scream — something quieter and more devastating. The sound of a man who has been *seen.*

"*The library,*" he says. His voice is smaller now. "*Behind the Byron collection. The documents. The accounts. All of it.*"

He looks at you with something that, in the living, you would call exhaustion.

"*You read well,*" he says. "*For someone with no power.*"

"I have plenty of power, sir. It's just the ordinary kind."

He vanishes. The room warms.

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 2
~ blackthorn.composure += 1
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['diplomatic'] += 2
~ blackthorn.money_location_revealed = True
~ blackthorn.lord_ashford_trust += 1

+ [The ghost is gone. The reading is done.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Aftermath

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Gothic
Something moves through you.

You don't choose it. It chooses you. The room, the candles, the cold, the *ghost* — it's all pressing against you and something inside you opens like a door you didn't know was there and the words come out in a voice that sounds like yours but *more.*

@if cards[4].name == "Three of Swords":
    "*The truth is written in SWORDS.* Three blades through the heart of everything you built. Betrayal. Theft. The tears you caused will ECHO beyond your grave—"
@elif cards[4].name == "Justice":
    "*JUSTICE.* The scales will BALANCE, Lord Blackthorn. Not even DEATH escapes the ledger. Your debts are DUE—"
@else:
    "*JUDGEMENT.* The trumpet SOUNDS. The dead will ANSWER for what they did in LIFE—"
@endif

The ghost screams. The candles explode — all of them, simultaneously, going out and then reigniting in a burst of blue flame. The table shakes. Your cards lift from the cloth and spin and settle again.

The ghost, terrified now: "*THE LIBRARY — THE BYRON COLLECTION — TAKE IT ALL, JUST LET ME REST—*"

He vanishes. Not fading — *fleeing.*

The room goes dark and then light and then normal and you are sitting at the table with your hands flat on the black cloth and you don't know what just happened.

You don't know what just happened.

Arabella: awed. "You *channeled* him—"

Dr. Blackwood: pen broken, ink on his shirt. "That was — that was—"

Ravencroft: on his feet, eyes burning: "*MAGNIFICENT—*"

Lady Blackthorn: smiling: "I *knew* you had The Gift."

Mrs. Winters, from the doorway, says nothing. But her expression — the one she reserves for serious things — is troubled.

~ blackthorn.gothic_persona += 3
~ blackthorn.groundedness -= 3
~ blackthorn.house_influence += 3
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['gothic'] += 2
~ blackthorn.money_location_revealed = True
~ blackthorn.lady_blackthorn_opinion += 3
~ blackthorn.winters_approval -= 2
~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 3

+ [Come back to yourself. Whatever that means now.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Aftermath

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Truth_Shaken
You can barely get the words out.

@if cards[4].name == "Three of Swords":
    "Three of Swords. Betrayal." You're speaking to the table, not to the room. Your voice is small. "He— the cards say he stole from the estate. And someone was hurt."
@elif cards[4].name == "Justice":
    "Justice. The— the accounts need to be settled." You're shaking. "There was theft. Hidden documents. The money—"
@else:
    "Judgement. The truth is— he hid things. The estate's finances are—" You can't finish. You gesture at the spread. "It's all there. The cards are quite clear."
@endif

It's not your best work. But the cards don't need your best work. They're doing the job on their own.

The ghost looks at the spread. Reads his own verdict in the images.

"*The library,*" he says, quieter. "*Behind Byron. Everything's there.*"

He vanishes. Not with drama — with the slow dissolution of someone who's been held together by secrets and has just had them removed.

The room warms. Your hands are still shaking.

Mrs. Winters brings you more tea. Sugar. The medicinal amount.

"You did fine, dear," she murmurs. "You got through it."

You drink the tea. You don't trust yourself to speak.

~ blackthorn.composure -= 2
~ blackthorn.interpretation_quality['panicked'] += 1
~ blackthorn.money_location_revealed = True
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 1

+ [It's over. You survived.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Aftermath

# ============================================================================
# SÉANCE AFTERMATH
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Seance_Aftermath
@py:
blackthorn.seance_completed = True
blackthorn.dominant_style = blackthorn.calculate_dominant_style()
session.seance_quality = blackthorn.calculate_seance_quality()
@endpy

Lady Blackthorn stands. She is *radiant.*

"Well. That was *productive.*" She turns to the room. "The Byron collection. Thomas, first thing tomorrow, if you would."

Thomas: "Yes, my lady."

"Splendid." She sweeps toward the door. Pauses. Turns back to you.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}. You are *everything* I hoped for. I shall write you the most *extraordinary* references."

She glides out. Miss Chen follows, pausing to give you a look — one eyebrow raised, the faintest nod. *Not bad.*

Dr. Blackwood stands, ink-stained and wild-eyed. "I have *SEVENTEEN PAGES* of notes. The acoustic properties of spectral vocalization alone — the thermal variance — I shall be writing papers for *YEARS—*"

He stumbles out, muttering about peer review.

Lord Ashford rises. He looks at you — really looks, for the first time all evening — with an expression that is less "brooding Gothic lord" and more "exhausted man who just watched something impossible."

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}. Thank you."

"I just read cards—"

"You read them *well.*" He pauses at the door. "I may... I may ask for a reading of my own. If you're willing. I have a... a situation."

"Of course, Lord Ashford."

He nods. Leaves.

Miss Arabella approaches you. Her eyes are bright. She takes your hand — hers is warm, surprisingly warm for someone so pale — and squeezes.

"You *heard* him," she whispers. "You heard the ghost. Even though you can't see them. The cards hear for you."

"I don't think that's how—"

"It *is.* It is and it's *wonderful.*"

She slips away.

The room is emptying. Thomas is snuffing candles. Mrs. Winters is clearing the table.

Lord Ravencroft has not moved. He is standing by his chair. Heathsniff is at his side.

They are both staring at you.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}—"

"Not tonight, Lord Ravencroft."

@if blackthorn.dominant_style == "gothic":
    He steps closer. "*What HAPPENED to you in there? I SAW it — the change — you became something MORE—*"

    "I became someone who needs to go to bed. *Immediately.* Goodnight."
@else:
    He steps closer. "You were *extraordinary—*"

    "I was doing my *job.* Which is now done. For the evening. Goodnight, Lord Ravencroft."
@endif

You leave before he can respond. Thomas holds the door for you. Slips you a biscuit from his pocket as you pass.

"For the shock," he whispers. "Mrs. Winters's recipe."

"Thank you, Thomas."

"First ghost?"

"*Obviously.*"

"You did better than the last one. She fainted. Twice."

"*Comforting.*"

~ blackthorn.thomas_friendliness += 2

You take your candle. You start up the stairs.

+ [Go straight to your room] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Encounter
+ [There is no option. You are going to your room. Immediately.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Encounter

# ============================================================================
# ACT 4: THE HALLWAY ENCOUNTER
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Encounter
The corridor is dark. Your candle throws jumping shadows. The portraits watch — you've stopped pretending they don't. Let them watch. You've just read tarot cards for a *ghost.* Painted eyes are nothing.

Your room is at the end of the hall. Twenty steps. Maybe thirty. You count them.

Twelve.

Thirteen.

Fourteen.

A figure steps from the shadows.

"*JESUS CHRIST—*"

Lord Ravencroft. Hair wild. Shirt billowing. WHY is his shirt BILLOWING? There is no wind in the HALLWAY. The wind is LOCALIZED to his PERSON.

"You."

"*Sir, it is PAST TWO IN THE MORNING—*"

"I couldn't sleep. Thinking about you. About the séance. About your *gift*—"

"I don't HAVE a gift—"

He steps closer. "The way you spoke to the spirit. {blackthorn.dominant_style == 'gothic' ? The way you TRANSFORMED — the power that moved through you — | Fearless. RESOLUTE. You stood before the dead and you did not WAVER —}"

"I was *TERRIFIED—*"

He steps closer. He smells like rain and moors and three days without bathing and something expensively masculine that was probably applied in front of a mirror with great deliberation.

"You're *different.* Not like the others. You *SEE* things—"

"I see that you've APPEARED FROM NOWHERE at an INAPPROPRIATE HOUR in your NIGHTSHIRT—"

"This isn't a nightshirt, it's a *POET'S* shirt—"

"It's a shirt with no BUTTONS, sir, and I can see your COLLARBONES—"

"*The cards called you here. To ME—*"

"The *NEWSPAPER* called me here, for *FIVE POUNDS*, which I am starting to think isn't *ENOUGH*—"

He takes your hand.

You pull it back.

"*SIR.* We are *not* engaged. You may not *grab*—"

"Forgive me. The *PASSION*— the *YEARNING*—"

"The *BOUNDARIES*, sir. *PERSONAL BOUNDARIES.*"

Heathsniff appears from the darkness. You didn't see him arrive. He materializes from a shadow like a long-snouted, silvery ghost and sits between you and Ravencroft.

The dog is providing a physical buffer.

The dog is on your side.

~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 2
~ blackthorn.heathsniff_affection += 2
~ blackthorn.ravencroft_encountered_hallway = True

+ [Scream for help.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Scream
+ [Tell him firmly and clearly to leave you alone.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Firm
+ [Ask him why. Why is he like this.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Why

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Scream
You open your mouth to scream.

You don't have to.

A door opens. Candlelight. Mrs. Winters in her nightgown and cap, holding a candlestick in one hand like a weapon and a look on her face that has been honed by forty years of managing aristocratic men who don't understand the word "no."

"Lord Ravencroft."

Ravencroft: "Mrs. Winters. I was merely—"

"Harassing the card reader at two in the morning. Yes. I can *see* that."

"*Thank you,* Mrs. Winters—"

Mrs. Winters steps into the hallway. She is five foot four and sixty-two years old and she is the most formidable thing in this house, including the ghost.

"Lord Ravencroft, return to your chambers."

"But I *MUST* speak with her—"

"At a *reasonable* hour. After *breakfast.* When she is *dressed* and *caffeinated.*"

Ravencroft: pouting — literally *pouting,* a grown man in a poet's shirt pouting in a hallway — "The moors call to me—"

"The moors will still be there in the morning."

He leaves. Dramatically. He even manages to make *walking down a corridor* look like the final scene of an opera. Heathsniff follows, pausing to look back at you with an expression that, on a human, would be an apology.

~ blackthorn.winters_rescue = True
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 2

+ [Let Mrs. Winters walk you back.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_WintersWalk

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Firm
"Lord Ravencroft. I have just conducted a reading for a *dead man.* I have been working since *midnight.* I am standing in a freezing corridor in a haunted house and my candle is going out and I need to use the privy and I am from *BATH* and I would like to go to my room and I would like you to *not be between me and my room.* Is that clear?"

A beat.

Ravencroft blinks. For a fraction of a second, something under all the performance surfaces — surprise. Genuine surprise. No one has ever been this direct with him.

"I... yes. Of course. Forgive me."

He steps aside. Heathsniff wags his tail. You walk past.

"Miss {blackthorn.player_name}—"

You turn.

"You were truly remarkable tonight." He says it quietly. Without the capital letters. It's the most human thing he's said all evening.

"Good *night,* Lord Ravencroft."

"Good night."

A door opens behind you. Mrs. Winters, in nightgown and cap, holding a candlestick.

"Everything alright, dear?"

"Under control, Mrs. Winters. But thank you."

"Hmm." She looks at Ravencroft's retreating figure. "First woman who's ever told him no. He won't know what to do with himself."

~ blackthorn.groundedness += 2
~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 1
~ blackthorn.winters_approval += 3

+ [Walk to your room. Mrs. Winters falls into step beside you.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_WintersWalk

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_Why
You stop pulling away. You look at him. Something about the hallway, the dark, the aftermath of a ghost — your defenses are down and your curiosity is up.

"*Why?*"

He blinks. "Why what?"

"Why do you *do* this? The dramatic entrances. The secret passages. The staring. The *shirt.* Why are you like this?"

For a moment — just a moment — the performance drops. His shoulders lower half an inch. His eyes lose the burning intensity and become, briefly, just... eyes. Tired eyes. Young eyes.

"I..." He stops. Starts again. "My parents were like this. My father used to appear in doorways and declaim Byron at my mother across rooms. She would swoon. He would catch her. I thought..."

"You thought that was how people are."

"Is it not?"

The question is so genuine it catches you off guard.

"No, Lord Ravencroft. It is not."

"Oh."

A door opens. Mrs. Winters, in her nightgown, holding a candlestick. She takes in the scene — you, Ravencroft, Heathsniff between you, the strange stillness of two people who've just had an accidental moment of honesty.

"Shall I...?"

"We're alright, Mrs. Winters. Lord Ravencroft was just saying goodnight."

He nods. "Yes. Goodnight. I... I apologize for the..." He gestures vaguely at himself — at the shirt, the hair, the whole situation. "...everything."

"Accepted. Provisionally."

He leaves. Quietly, for once. Heathsniff follows, but gives your hand one soft lick before departing.

~ blackthorn.ravencroft_fixation += 1
~ blackthorn.groundedness += 1
~ blackthorn.heathsniff_affection += 2
~ blackthorn.arabella_connection += 1

+ [Head for your room. Mrs. Winters is already there.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_WintersWalk

# ============================================================================
# MRS. WINTERS WALKS YOU BACK
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Hallway_WintersWalk
@if blackthorn.winters_rescue:
    Mrs. Winters walks you to the Rose Room. Her candlelight is steadier than yours — forty years of practice.

    "Is he always like that?" you ask.

    "Since he was fifteen. His parents were the same. Very... Byronic."

    "He came out of *nowhere*—"

    "The house has passages. In the walls. He uses them. For *drama.*"

    "This is a *nightmare—*"

    "It's a weekend house party, dear. Same thing, really."
@else:
    Mrs. Winters falls into step beside you, uninvited but entirely welcome. She's been hovering near your corridor. You suspect she heard the whole thing.

    "You handled that well."

    "I handled a *ghost* tonight, Mrs. Winters. Lord Ravencroft is almost restful by comparison."

    She almost smiles. Almost. "You'd be the first to think so."
@endif

She walks you to the Rose Room door. The corridor is dark and the portraits watch and somewhere in the house something creaks that is probably settling beams and is possibly not.

"Mrs. Winters."

"Yes, dear?"

"The ghost. Is this... does this happen often?"

She considers the question. "In this house? More than you'd think. Less than you'd fear."

"That's not reassuring."

"It wasn't meant to be." She pauses. "The last card reader — the one who fled?"

"Thomas mentioned her."

"She couldn't handle it. The house. The guests. The things you see here that you can't explain." She looks at you with eyes that have seen six housemaids come and go and three mistresses and two curses and a poltergeist. "But you. You read for a *ghost* tonight. Sat at the table and read him his cards like he was a widow in Cheltenham wanting to know about her nephew. That takes something."

"It takes being from Bath. We're very stubborn there."

"I know. I'm from Wells."

"That's practically Bath."

"Don't tell anyone." She puts a hand on your arm. "Try to sleep, dear. Tomorrow will be... eventful."

"More eventful than *tonight?*"

"Lord Ashford's transformation is in two nights. Things will get worse before they get better."

"His *what*—"

"Goodnight, dear." She closes the door.

~ blackthorn.servant_trust += 2

+ [Go to bed.] -> Blackthorn.Session1.Bed

# ============================================================================
# ACT 5: BED
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.Bed
@py:
blackthorn.session_grade = blackthorn.calculate_session_grade()
@endpy

You sit on the bed. The Rose Room. The supernatural cold. The roaring fire that accomplishes nothing.

Your tarot deck is on the nightstand. You pick it up. The cards are warm. They shouldn't be warm — the room is freezing — but they are. They've been warm all night, you realize. Even at the séance, even when the ghost was screaming and the frost was climbing the windows, the cards in your hand were warm.

You hold them.

A ghost spoke to you tonight.

Not metaphorically. Not symbolically. A dead man materialized at a table and looked at your cards and the cards *worked.* They worked the same way they always work — patterns, symbols, the reader's skill at translating image into meaning — except this time, the subject was dead and the subject *confirmed* the reading.

You don't know what to do with that.

@if blackthorn.session_grade == "solid":
    You are from Bath. You learned this from a book. Nothing that happened tonight changes that.

    But something that happened tonight *adds* to it.

    The cards worked for a ghost. Your skill — the mundane, learned-from-a-book, three-shillings-at-Hatchards skill — translates across the veil. Not because you're special. Not because you have "The Gift." Because the cards are the cards and the reader is the reader and the skill is the skill, whether the client is alive or dead.

    This is either the most terrifying thing you've ever realized or the most comforting.

    You're not sure which.
@elif blackthorn.session_grade == "steady":
    You are from Bath. You learned this from a book. You are shaken but not broken.

    The ghost was real. The reading was real. You are, against all evidence and personal preference, in a house where the dead walk and the paintings watch and dinner is at midnight and there are wolves.

    You survived tonight. You read for a ghost and you survived.

    You can do this. Probably.

    You are from Bath.
@elif blackthorn.session_grade == "shaken":
    You are from Bath.

    You repeat it like a ward. Like a prayer. Like something that might keep the dark at bay.

    *I am from Bath. I learned this from a book. I am a professional. I read cards for a living and tonight I read them for a dead man and the dead man screamed and told us where the money was and this is my life now.*

    You pull the blankets up. All of them. The cold seeps through anyway.

    You'll get through this weekend. You will. You're stubborn and competent and from Bath and those things have to count for *something.*
@else:
    You don't know who you are.

    That's the thought that keeps you awake. Not the ghost — the ghost was terrifying, but ghosts are ghosts, they're an event, you can process an event. What you can't process is the moment in the séance when you felt something else move through you. Something that used your voice and your cards and your hands but wasn't quite *you.*

    Lady Blackthorn called it The Gift.

    You called it a skill, from a book, from Bath.

    What if it's both?

    The house seems to breathe around you. The fire crackles. The cold presses in.

    You hold your deck against your chest and try to remember who you were before tonight.
@endif

From outside: a wolf howls. Low, long, anguished.

And beneath it: Heathsniff, howling in unison. Slightly more theatrical.

@if blackthorn.session_grade != "compromised":
    You think: *I hate it here.*

    You think: *Two more days.*

    You think: *I'm going to need more tea.*
@else:
    You think: *Something is happening to me.*

    You think: *This house is doing something to me.*

    You think: *I need to talk to Mrs. Winters.*
@endif

You sleep.

Fitfully. Briefly. In the spaces between wolf howls and the creak of a house that breathes around you.

You dream within the dream — layers of sleep, impossible architecture — and in the dream within the dream you're in your apartment, at your reading table, and there's a borzoi lying on your feet and you don't mind.

+ [Wake up. (End of Session)] -> Blackthorn.Session1.DreamFade

# ============================================================================
# DREAM FADE
# ============================================================================

:: Blackthorn.Session1.DreamFade
@py:
# Reader progression rewards
reader.sessions_completed += 1
reader.mystical_affinity += 1

if blackthorn.session_grade == "solid":
    reader.competence += 2
    reader.empathy += 1
elif blackthorn.session_grade == "steady":
    reader.competence += 1
    reader.empathy += 1
elif blackthorn.session_grade == "shaken":
    reader.competence += 1
elif blackthorn.session_grade == "compromised":
    reader.self_doubt = True
    reader.insight += 1  # You learn from being overwhelmed

# Bleed-through objects — dream residue in the waking world
blackthorn.bleed_objects = ["calling_card"]  # Always
if blackthorn.heathsniff_affection >= 2:
    blackthorn.bleed_objects.append("borzoi_hair")
if blackthorn.session_grade in ["solid", "steady"]:
    blackthorn.bleed_objects.append("biscuit")
@endpy

Morning. Your apartment. Your reading table.

The dream doesn't fade so much as *fold.* Like someone closing a book — carefully, with a bookmark, intending to return.

You sit up. Your deck is on the nightstand. Your real nightstand.

And next to it:

@if "calling_card" in blackthorn.bleed_objects:
A calling card. Yellowed, brittle, impossible. Engraved in copperplate script:

[!beat]Lord Desmond Blackthorn. Blackthorn Manor, Yorkshire. 1873.[/!beat]

It smells like beeswax and cold stone. It is over a hundred years old and it appeared on your nightstand this morning.
@endif

@if "borzoi_hair" in blackthorn.bleed_objects:

A single hair. Long, silvery, impossibly fine. The kind of hair that belongs to a borzoi of exceptional breeding and theatrical disposition.

You hold it up to the light. It gleams.

"Sniffy," you say, without knowing why.
@endif

@if "biscuit" in blackthorn.bleed_objects:

And — wrapped in a cloth napkin, still *warm,* which is physically impossible — a biscuit. Shortbread. The kind a housekeeper from Wells would make.

You eat it. It tastes like butter and kindness and the firm belief that a cup of tea solves most things.
@endif

You sit at your reading table. Look at the objects. The impossible made tangible.

@if blackthorn.session_grade == "solid":
    You are from Bath. You learned tarot from a book.

    And apparently, that's enough.

    For a ghost. For a Gothic manor. For a poet-shirted lord and his matching dog.

    Your book didn't prepare you for this. But *you* were prepared, whether the book knew it or not.

    You shuffle your deck. Draw a card.

    The Star.

    "Of course," you say. And you almost laugh.
@elif blackthorn.session_grade == "steady":
    You are from Bath. You learned tarot from a book. You read for a ghost and you lived to tell about it.

    You're going back. You know you're going back. The dream isn't finished — the calling card on your nightstand is proof of that. Lord Ashford needs help. Miss Arabella sees ghosts. Thomas deserves better employers. Mrs. Winters deserves backup.

    And Lord Ravencroft needs... something. You're not sure what. Possibly a firm talking-to and a different shirt.

    You shuffle your deck. Draw a card.

    The Fool.

    "New journey," you mutter. "Wonderful."
@elif blackthorn.session_grade == "shaken":
    You are from Bath. You learned tarot from a book.

    You keep saying it. It keeps being true. But the edges of it feel less certain now — not because you've changed, but because the world turned out to be bigger than you thought.

    There's a calling card on your nightstand from a dead man. Your book did not cover this.

    You'll go back. You know you will. Someone has to be the sensible one.

    You shuffle your deck. Draw a card.

    The Moon.

    "Dreams and reality," you say. "Bleeding together."

    You set the card down.

    You make tea.
@else:
    You sit at your reading table.

    You hold your deck.

    You don't shuffle. You just hold it.

    Something happened to you in that house. Something moved through you. And the worst part isn't the ghost or the cold or the wind-from-nowhere — the worst part is that it felt *right.* For one moment, at the séance table, you weren't Miss {blackthorn.player_name} from Bath who learned tarot from a book. You were something else. Something the house recognized. Something it *wanted.*

    You need to go back. Not because of Lord Ashford or Miss Arabella or the servants.

    Because you need to find out what you are.

    You shuffle your deck. The cards are warm.

    You draw The Tower.

    You stare at it for a very long time.
@endif

~ reader.blackthorn_resonance = "permanent"

+ [Return to your day. Two more nights at Blackthorn Manor await.] -> ReaderTable

